  "llm_summary": "## Multi-Layer Gene Expression Analysis: B Cell Activation Genes in Systemic Lupus Erythematosus\n\nThis comprehensive analysis identified 30 genes involved in B cell activation (GO:0042113) and examined their dysregulation in systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) using a three-layer approach combining knowledge graphs, single-cell RNA-seq, and bulk validation data. At the tissue level in blood, 9 genes showed upregulation with fold changes >1.5, led by ICOSLG (3.17-fold), CD19 (3.0-fold), and FCGR2B (3.0-fold). However, this tissue-level summary masks striking cell-type-specific differences, where the same genes can show opposite regulatory patterns across different immune cell populations.\n\nThe cell-type analysis revealed that **lymphocytes are the primary drivers of B cell activation gene upregulation in SLE**, with 9 upregulated and only 1 downregulated gene. Key upregulated genes in lymphocytes include the B cell marker CD19, the apoptosis regulator BAX, phospholipase signaling components (PLCL2, PLCG2), the co-stimulatory molecule ICOSLG, and the inhibitory Fc receptor FCGR2B. In stark contrast, all other major immune cell types showed predominantly downregulation of these same genes: natural killer cells (0 up, 16 down), CD4+ T cells (0 up, 15 down), classical monocytes (0 up, 19 down), and even B cells themselves (0 up, 19 down). This paradoxical pattern suggests that the \"lymphocyte\" population driving upregulation may represent activated or pathogenic B cell subsets not captured in the broader \"B cell\" category.\n\nBulk RNA-seq validation across 10 independent studies (GSE72420, GSE72509, GSE80183, GSE92387, GSE92472, and others) strongly confirmed the single-cell findings, with CD19 showing the most dramatic upregulation (166-fold, log2FC=7.38), followed by FCGR2B (21-fold, log2FC=4.42) and PLCG2 (13-fold, log2FC=3.67). The validation extends beyond the top hits, with ICOSLG showing 3.7-fold upregulation and more modest but consistent increases in IRF2BP2, PLCL2, and ATP11C. Only HSPD1 showed downregulation in bulk samples, aligning with its mixed single-cell patterns.\n\nThese findings suggest that SLE involves aberrant activation of specific B cell subpopulations that highly express canonical B cell activation machinery, while other immune cells show compensatory downregulation. The robust validation across multiple GEO datasets strengthens confidence in CD19, FCGR2B, and PLCG2 as key dysregulated B cell activation genes in SLE, potentially representing therapeutic targets or biomarkers for monitoring disease activity in this complex autoimmune disorder."
